paragraphs.title: Welcome
paragraphs.text:
%md

this notebook is manipulating raw N-Quads of the [webdatacomons](http://webdatacommons.org/structureddata/2015-11/stats/how_to_get_the_data.html) in order to extract a subset representing a particular topic, in our case Nantes, a French city. 

we will :
 - Do basic observations on the data using filtering and counting 
 - Create a filter representing our basic Nantes. 
 - Join the data with itself to extend the neighbourhood.

### RDF predicates 
A first look at the data and some basic aggregate count later, we see what are the most popular predicate on webages. 

 - rdf:type is the most common and that make sense! 15-25% estimate
 - vcard addresses seems more comon than schema.org addresses
 - Schema.org has many Address predicates 
 - ... Take a look 


### rdf:types Objects 

Similarly, we can observe the rdf:type predicate and see what types of objects it describes the most. using filtering we can refine our search

%md
## Nantes
We look for predicate that describes Nantes with as much uniqness as possible 
![nantes](http://2.bp.blogspot.com/-MmfbKKSdmjo/UTxMsc2BBuI/AAAAAAAACpg/BqyLgO3A3Z0/s1600/Elephant+Nantes+1.JPG)

### Basic filtering 
Applied to the whole data in a single read.
We search for a few post code matching the city and the city name inside the NQuads.
We filter the search on some very specific predicate. 




## Sibligns
Here comes the issue, to find any form of neighbourhood we need to join the data to the original dataset. if its a small set then we can broadcast but here is the general method. 

#### Parent
Capturing the parent node enable a second row much faster 

### Graph and Subject
A problem of the raw input is that it does not distinguish between subjet String, IRI, or blank node.
Therefore, the join need to be done using both columns.

paragraphs.title: Nantes
paragraphs.text:
%spark.sql

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS nantes 
SELECT predicate, object, graph, subject FROM data
WHERE   
    (   
        ( 
            predicate = "<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#postal-code>"
            OR 
            predicate LIKE "<http://schema.org%postalCode>"
        )
        AND object IN ('44000','44100','44200','44300')
        
    )OR( 
        (
            predicate LIKE "<http://schema.org%addressLocality>"
            OR
            predicate = "<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#locality>"
            OR
            predicate = "<http://purl.org/dc/terms/title>"
        )
        AND object LIKE "%Nantes%" 
    )

paragraphs.title: Sibligns and the parent
paragraphs.text:
%spark.sql

CREATE TABLE IF NOT EXISTS hop1
SELECT d.predicate, d.object, d.graph, d.subject 
FROM data d
RIGHT JOIN nantes n ON (d.subject = n.subject
                        OR 
                        d.object = n.subject) 
                    AND 
                        d.graph = n.graph 
WHERE d.predicate LIKE '%vcard%' 
  OR  d.predicate LIKE '%rdf-syntax%type%'

paragraphs.title: Address card
paragraphs.text:
import spark.implicits._

var addressCard = sqlContext.sql("SELECT * FROM oneOfEach")
    .where("predicate LIKE '%vcard%' OR predicate LIKE '%rdf-syntax%type%'")
    .groupBy("graph","subject")
    .pivot("predicate")
    .agg(concat_ws(" ", collect_list("object")))
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type>","type")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml/microdata#item>","microdata")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#street-address>","street-address")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#postal-code>","postcode")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#locality>","locality")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#region>","region")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#country-name>","country-name")
    //.where("locality NOT LIKE '%JAL%'")

addressCard.show
addressCard.registerTempTable("addressCard")

paragraphs.title: Pivoting the predicate column
paragraphs.text:
%md
After we've grouped our data together, we begin to see patterns but also noise. more importantly, Entities remain as different rows and we would like to assemble them together.  

In order to find the address card we need to associate the predicates representing an address together. we use pivoting to do so since we already have already extracted the data

paragraphs.title: All exec
paragraphs.text:
import spark.implicits._

var all = spark.read
            .parquet("open-data-plus/results/parq_other")
            .where("predicate LIKE '%vcard%' OR predicate LIKE '%rdf-syntax%type%'")

var init = all
    .where("""(( predicate = '<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#postal-code>'
                    OR 
                predicate = '<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#postal-code>')
              AND 
                object IN ('44000','44100','44200','44300'))
             OR
             ((predicate LIKE "<http://schema.org%addressLocality>"
                OR
               predicate = "<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#locality>"
                OR
               predicate = "<http://purl.org/dc/terms/title>"
                 )
              AND
                 object LIKE "%Nantes%")
            """
    )  
    .withColumnRenamed("graph","g")
    .withColumnRenamed("subject","s")
    .withColumnRenamed("predicate","p")
    .withColumnRenamed("object","o")
    
var hop = all
    .join(init, all("graph") === init("g") 
                        && all("subject") === init("s"), "right")

//hop.show
 
var addressCard = hop
    .groupBy("graph","subject")
    .pivot("predicate")
    .agg(concat_ws(" ", collect_list("object")))
    
addressCard.withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/1999/02/22-rdf-syntax-ns#type>","type")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml/microdata#item>","microdata")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#street-address>","street-address")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#postal-code>","postcode")
    .withColumnRenamed("<http://www.w3.org/2006/vcard/ns#locality>","locality")
    .where("locality NOT LIKE '%JAL%'")
    .registerTempTable("addressCard")

paragraphs.text:
%md 
# File conversion

In order to convert the file to a column based structured parquet file, we match a regexp, the unzipping (.gz) is handled natively by spark, the regexp being greedy and buggy we filter big lines (> 2000 char) mostly articleBody vectors or the like. we loose some information there but avoid as well a lot of noise. 


### REGEX

The regular expression capture 4 groups Some filtering needs to be done afterwards.


### Writing result

Results get written to parquet by the cluster without going through driver program.

paragraphs.title: Convert to parquet
paragraphs.text:
import scala.util.matching.Regex
import spark.implicits._

case class Quad(subject: String, predicate: String, objet: String, graph: String)

var originalPattern = 
    "^(<[^\\s]+>|_:(?:[A-Za-z][A-Za-z0-9\\-_]*))\\s+(<[^\\s]+>)\\s+(<[^\\s]+>|_:(?:[A-Za-z][A-Za-z0-9\\-_]*)|\\\"(?:(?:\\\"|[^\"])*)\\\"(?:@(?:[a-z]+[\\-A-Za-z0-9]*)|\\^\\^<(?:[^>]+)>)?)\\s+(<[^\\s]+>).*$".r



spark.read	
    .textFile(
	            "open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-embedded-jsonld.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-adr.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-geo.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-hcalendar.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-hcard.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-hlisting.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-hrecipe.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-hresume.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-hreview.nq-00000.gz",
				"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-mf-xfn.nq-00000.gz",
            	"open-data-plus/dump/dpef.html-microdata.nq-00005.gz"
    )	
	.filter(line => line.length < 2000)     //fancy regex overflow 
	.map(s => {
	    val res = originalPattern.findFirstMatchIn(s) match {
            case Some(m) =>
                println(m.group(1))
                Quad(m.group(1) , m.group(2), m.group(3), m.group(4) ) 
            case None =>
                println("There wasn't a match ! ") 
                Quad("","","","")
        }
        res
	})
	.filter(q => q != null)		                    // unfortonately spark map isn't filtering null
	.withColumnRenamed("objet","object")            // Because .. ho well 
	.write
	.bucketBy(4, "graph")
	.sortBy("graph")
	.saveAsTable("oneOfEach2");
	
	
// CHECK THE RESULT 
spark.sql("SELECT * FROM oneOfEach")
    .show();
